    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Two Parties, for Better or Worse</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Mark Risk letter disputes August 20 editorial which criticized Ralph Nader, Green Party presidential candidate</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Two Visions of Government'' (editorial, Aug. 20):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Two Visions of Government'' (editorial, Aug. 20):</p>
        <p>You respond to Ralph Nader's claim that there are no differences between the major political parties with a catalog of contrasting positions on specific policy issues.</p>
        <p>There are indeed obvious differences between the stated positions of George W. Bush and Al Gore. But there is also an unmistakable narrowing of the national debate on issues of social spending, defense and infrastructure investment, which might be related to the high rate of return of incumbents to office, campaign finance laws that facilitate interest-group politics and constantly falling electoral participation.</p>
        <p>Reinvigorating democratic political competition is a difficult problem. Mr. Nader may not be exactly right, but surely he is not a straw man.</p>
        <p>MARK RISK  New York, Aug. 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
